{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478631"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17531"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17531"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.02,0.67,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115493"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10221"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2932"},{"type":"tags","id":"3504"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45221"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115493"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of vomiting and abdominal pain. His parent reports increased thirst and urination over the past two weeks, with a 3 kg weight loss. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 135/min (reference range for age 70-140), blood pressure 95/60 mmHg (reference range for age systolic blood pressure 80-115), respiratory rate 32/min (reference range for age 15-30) with deep sighing breaths, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is lethargic but rousable. His CRT is 4 seconds, mouth is dry, and his eyes are sunken. His breath has a sweet, fruity odour. His abdomen is soft but diffusely tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insulin infusion","Potassium replacement","Sodium bicarbonate infusion","Normal saline bolus","Venous blood glucose measurement"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), including polyuria, polydipsia, weight loss, vomiting, lethargy, and Kussmaul breathing (deep, sighing respirations). The fruity breath odour suggests ketosis. The physical examination reveals significant dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing the primary survey approach to the unwell child using the ABCDE method and addressing issues as they are identified, assessment of circulation in this case would reveal signs of moderate dehydration (sunken eyes, dry mucous membranes, prolonged CRT with vitals remaining within normal limits) and therefore correcting this via a \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal saline bolus\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. In paediatric DKA, fluid resuscitation takes precedence over insulin therapy. Children with DKA are typically 5-10% dehydrated, and careful fluid replacement is crucial to prevent cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood glucose measurement\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed promptly, the patient\u0027s severe dehydration identified during the circulation assessment of the primary survey requires immediate fluid resuscitation. The clinical presentation strongly suggests DKA - the first step in managing this patient\u0027s suspected DKA is with fluids. Bloods for a venous glucose level might be obtained at the time of cannula insertion to guide subsequent management; however, the results of a venous gas would not be available immediately. Waiting for them could compromise patient care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E should not be given before fluid resuscitation is initiated. Insulin administration without adequate fluid replacement can increase the risk of cerebral oedema, a potentially fatal complication of paediatric DKA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely indicated in DKA, even with severe acidosis. The acidosis will correct with appropriate fluid and insulin therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium replacement\u003C/strong\u003E will likely be needed, but not as the first step. Despite total body potassium depletion, serum potassium may initially be normal or elevated due to acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial fluid resuscitation, the subsequent management includes careful monitoring of vital signs, neurological status, and biochemical parameters, followed by initiation and careful titration of an insulin infusion. The goal is to gradually correct the metabolic derangements while avoiding complications, particularly cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diabetic ketoacidosis in children presents with dehydration, Kussmaul breathing, and a characteristic smell of ketones.","Initial presentation of type 1 diabetes typically includes polyuria, polydipsia and weight loss over days to weeks.","Altered mental state and vomiting suggest severe diabetic ketoacidosis requiring urgent intervention."],"references":["Pasi R, Ravi KS. Type 1 diabetes mellitus in pediatric age group: A rising endemic. J Family Med Prim Care. 2022 Jan;11(1):27-31. doi: 10.4103/jfmpc.jfmpc_975_21. Epub 2022 Jan 31. PMID: 35309606; PMCID: PMC8930152."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17531"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T09:15:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T19:26:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10221"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115493"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"